SIMPLE: trinomial
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trinomial
<hw>Tri*no"mi*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>tri-</ets> + <ets>-nomial</ets> as in <ets>binomial</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>trin⟦ocir⟧me</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A quantity
consisting of three terms, connected by the sign + or -; <as>as,
<mathex>x + y + z</mathex>, or <mathex>ax + 2b -
c<exp>2</exp></mathex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trinomial</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trinomial
<hw>Tri*no"mi*al</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld>
<def>Consisting of three terms; of or pertaining to trinomials; <as>as,
a <ex>trinomial</ex> root</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Nat. Hist.)</fld> <def>Consisting of, or involving
the use of, three terms; <as>as, a <ex>trinomial</ex> systematic name
specifying the genus, species, and variety</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trinominal</ent>⟦br⟧
